                <h1>The Minimum Spanning Tree Algorithm</h1>
                <p>
                    A telecommunication company wants to connect all the bl=
ocks in a new neighborhood. However, the easiest possibility to install new=
 cables is to bury them along roads. So the company decides to use hubs whi=
ch are placed at road junctions. How can the cost be minimized if the price=
 for connecting two hubs corresponds to the length of the cable attaching t=
hem?=20
				</p>
				<p>
					Considering the roads as a graph, the above example is an instance of =
the Minimum Spanning Tree problem. Prim's and Kruskal's algorithms are two =
notable algorithms which can be used to find the minimum subset of edges in=
 a weighted undirected graph connecting all nodes.</p>
                <h2>This tutorial presents Kruskal's algorithm which calcul=
ates the minimum spanning tree (MST) of a connected weighted graphs. If the=
 graph is not connected the algorithm will find a minimum spannig forest (M=
SF). For a comparison you can also find an introduction to <a href=3D"https=
://algorithms.discrete.ma.tum.de/graph-algorithms/mst-prim/index_en.html">P=
rim's algorithm</a>.</h2>
